ed by the user, and which contains \"all\" useful information a support person might need to debug what's going on. In the Syncthing case, this could take the form of an API method (and menu option in the GUI) that results in a zip file download. In this zip file we would have\r\n\r\n- A text file with basic build info (version / platform)\r\n- The current configuration\r\n- The last few log lines, whatever we have cached in memory\r\n- Any panic files we can find in the config directory\r\n- The contents of the usage reporting data (this would include things like the benchmark and folder sizes which is good to know)\r\n- Maybe, a heap and CPU profile (just a couple of seconds for CPU in that case)\r\n- â€¦?\r\n\r\nMost of this isn't super privacy invasive, possibly excepting folder/device IDs. Potentially we could allow redaction of those in a systematic manner (better we do it than the user, as we then know *how* the config/logs have been mangled). Potentially we could also encrypt the zip file with a random password or similar, so it needs to be explicitly handed over to be understood.\r\n\r\nWe might also want to auto-redact API keys and username / password hashes from the config, as those are never interesting to the recipient. (Whether they are set *at all* or not might be interesting, so we should not just remove them - just set them to `*redacted*` or something if present.)\r\n","closed_by":{"login":"calmh","id":125426,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEyNTQyNg==","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/125426?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/calmh","html_url":"https://github.com/calmh","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/calmh/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/calmh/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/calmh/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/calmh/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/calmh/subscriptions","or